While exploring the [[Marias River]] in 1806, the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] came within {{convert|50|mi|km|0}} of the area that is now the park.<ref name="overview"/> A series of explorations after 1850 helped to shape the understanding of the area that later became the park. In 1885, [[George Bird Grinnell]] hired noted explorer (and later well regarded author) [[James Willard Schultz]] to guide him on a hunting expedition into what would later become the park.<ref name="Hanna">{{cite book |last=Hanna |first=Warren L |title=The Life and Times of James Willard Schultz (Apikuni) |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=Norman, Oklahoma |isbn=0-8061-1985-3 |chapter=Exploring With Grinnell |pages=133<U+2013>145 |year=1986}}</ref>  After several more trips to the region, Grinnell became so inspired by the scenery that he spent the next two decades working to establish a national park. In 1901, Grinnell wrote a description of the region, in which he referred to it as the "Crown of the Continent", and his efforts to protect the land make him the premier contributor to this cause.<ref name="Century">{{Cite journal| last = Grinnell| first = George Bird| title = The Crown of the Continent| journal = The Century Magazine| volume = 62| pages = 660<U+2013>672| publisher = MacMillan and Co.| location = London| date = May 1901 to October 1901| url = http://books.google.com/?id=WIPPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA660&lpg=PA660&dq=The+crown+of+the+continent+in+Century+magazine&q| accessdate =2010-04-13}}</ref> A few years after Grinnell first visited, [[Henry L. Stimson]] and two companions, including a Blackfoot, climbed the steep east face of [[Chief Mountain]] in 1892.

[[File:Many glacier hotel.jpg|thumb|right|The Many Glacier Hotel on [[Swiftcurrent Lake]]]]

In 1891, the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] crossed the Continental Divide at [[Marias Pass]] {{convert|5213|ft|m|0}}, which is along the southern boundary of the park. In an effort to stimulate use of the railroad, the Great Northern soon advertised the splendors of the region to the public. The company lobbied the [[United States Congress]], and in 1897, the park was designated as a forest preserve.<ref name="Spence2">{{Cite journal| last = Spence| first = Mark David| title = Crown of the Continent, Backbone of the World| journal = Environmental History| volume = 1| page =35| publisher = Forest History Society| location = Durham, NC| date = July 1996| url = http://www.jstor.org/stable/3985155| accessdate =2010-04-13| issue = 3}}{{registration required}}</ref> Under the forest designation mining was still allowed, but was not commercially successful. Meanwhile, proponents of protecting the region kept up their efforts, and in 1910, under the influence of George Bird Grinnell, [[Henry L. Stimson]] and the railroad, a bill was introduced into the U.S. Congress which redesignated the region from a forest reserve to a national park. This bill was signed into law by President [[William Howard Taft]] on May 11, 1910.<ref name="Centennial">{{cite web| title =Glacier Centennial 2010| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/parknews/glacier-centennial-2010.htm|date=2009-02-17 | accessdate = 2010-04-13}}</ref> From May until August, the forest reserve supervisor, Fremont Nathan Haines, managed the Park's resources as the first acting superintendent. In August 1910, William Logan was appointed the Park's first superintendent. While the designation of the forest reserve confirmed the traditional usage rights of the Blackfeet, the enabling legislation of the National Park does not mention the guarantees to the Native Americans. It is the position of the United States government, that with the special designation as a National Park the mountains ceded their multi-purpose ''public land status'' and the former rights ceased to exist as it was confirmed by the Court of Claims in 1935. Some Blackfeet held that their traditional usage rights still exist ''de jure''. In the 1980s armed standoffs were avoided narrowly several times.<ref name="Spence3">{{Cite journal| last = Spence| first = Mark David| title = Crown of the Continent, Backbone of the World| journal = Environmental History| volume = 1| pages =40<U+2013>41| publisher = Forest History Society| location = Durham, NC| date = July 1996| url = http://www.jstor.org/stable/3985155| accessdate =2010-04-13| issue = 3}}{{registration required}}</ref>

The Great Northern Railway, under the supervision of president Louis W. Hill, built a number of hotels and [[chalet]]s throughout the park in the 1910s to promote tourism.  These buildings, constructed and operated by a Great Northern subsidiary called the [[Glacier Park Company]], were modeled on Swiss architecture as part of Hill's plan to portray Glacier as "America's Switzerland". Vacationers commonly took pack trips on horseback between the lodges or utilized the seasonal stagecoach routes to gain access to the [[Many Glacier]] area in the northeast.<ref name="many">{{cite web| title =Many Glacier Hotel Historic Structure Report| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/mghiststr.pdf |format=PDF |date= July 2002 |accessdate = 2010-04-13}}</ref>

The chalets, built between 1910 and 1913, included [[Belton Chalets|Belton]], St. Mary, Going-to-the-Sun, Many Glacier, Two Medicine, [[Sperry Chalet|Sperry]], [[Granite Park Chalet|Granite Park]], Cut Bank, and Gunsight Lake. The railway also built [[Glacier Park Lodge]], adjacent to the park on its east side, and the [[Many Glacier Hotel]] on the east shore of [[Swiftcurrent Lake]]. Louis Hill personally selected the sites for all of these buildings, choosing each for their dramatic scenic backdrops and views. Another developer, John Lewis, built the Lewis Glacier Hotel on [[Lake McDonald]] in 1913<U+2013>1914. The Great Northern Railway bought the hotel in 1930, and it was later renamed [[Lake McDonald Lodge]].<ref name="lm">{{cite web| last =Harrison| first =Laura Soulli<U+00E8>re| title =Lake McDonald Lodge| work =Architecture in the Parks| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior| year =2001| url =http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/harrison/harrison9.htm| accessdate = 2010-04-13}}</ref>  Some of the chalets were in remote backcountry locations accessible only by trail. Today, only Sperry, Granite Park, and Belton Chalets are still in operation, while a building formerly belonging to Two Medicine Chalet is now [[Two Medicine Store]].<ref name="Djuff">{{cite book| last = Djuff| first = Ray| title = View with a Room:  Glacier's Historic Hotels and Chalets| publisher = Farcountry Press |location= Helena, Montana| year = 2001| isbn = 1-56037-170-6 |page= 52}}</ref> The surviving chalet and hotel buildings within the park are now designated as [[National Historic Landmarks]].<ref name="gn">{{cite web| last =Harrison| first =Laura Soulli<U+00E8>re| title =Great Northern Railway Buildings| work =Architecture in the Parks| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior| year =1986| url =http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/harrison/harrison8.htm| accessdate = 2010-04-13}}</ref>  In total, 350 buildings and structures within the park are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], including ranger stations, backcountry patrol cabins, fire lookouts, and concession facilities.<ref name="management1">{{cite web| title =General Management Plan| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior|month= April | year= 1999| page=49| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/gmpfinal.pdf| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20070127084050/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/gmpfinal.pdf| archivedate =2007-01-27| format=PDF| accessdate = 2010-04-14}}</ref>

[[File:Going to the Sun Mountain 1932.jpg|thumb|Road construction along the [[Going-to-the-Sun Road]] with [[Going to the Sun Mountain]] in background, 1932]]

After the park was well established and visitors began to rely more on automobiles, work was begun on the {{convert|53|mi|km|0}} long [[Going-to-the-Sun Road]], completed in 1932. Also known simply as the Sun Road, the road bisects the park and is the only route that ventures deep into the park, going over the Continental Divide at [[Logan Pass]], {{convert|6646|ft|m|0}} at the midway point. The Sun Road is also listed on the National Register of Historic Places, and in 1985 was designated a [[National Historic Civil Engineering Landmark]].<ref name="Guthrie">{{cite book| last = Guthrie| first = C. W.| title = Going-To-The-Sun Road: Glacier National Park's Highway to the Sky | publisher = Farcountry Press |location=Helena, Montana | year = 2006 |isbn=978-1-56037-335-3|page= 8}}</ref> Another route, along the southern boundary between the park and [[United States National Forest|National Forests]] is [[U.S. Route 2]], which crosses the Continental Divide at Marias Pass and connects the towns of West Glacier and [[East Glacier Park Village, Montana|East Glacier]].  During the 1930s, the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] assisted in the development of many of the park's trails and campgrounds.  The increase in motor vehicle traffic through the park during the 1930s also resulted in the construction of new concession facilities at [[Swiftcurrent Auto Camp Historic District|Swiftcurrent]] and [[Rising Sun (Montana)|Rising Sun]], both designed for automobile-based tourism.  These early auto camps are now also listed on the National Register.<ref name="Djuff"/>

In 2011, Glacier National Park was honored on the seventh quarter in the [[America the Beautiful Quarters]] series.<ref>[http://www.usmint.gov/mint_programs/atb/?local=Glacier The United States Mint Coins and Medals Program<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

==Park management==
[[File:GlacierNP L7 20010701.jpg|thumb|right|[[Landsat 7]] image of [[Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park]]. The [[Rocky Mountain Front]] formed by the Lewis Overthrust fault rises dramatically above the Great Plains on the right.]]

Glacier National Park is managed by the [[National Park Service]]; park headquarters is in West Glacier, Montana. Visitation to Glacier National Park averages slightly less than {{Nowrap|2 million}} visitors annually, however a relative few venture far from main roadways and hotels.

Glacier National Park had an operating budget of $13,190,000 for fiscal year 2008. The 2008 budget was an increase over 2007 and was used to increase employee staffing levels, but monies for maintenance projects and road work was not forthcoming.<ref name="budget">{{cite web| title = 2008 Budget for Glacier National Park| publisher = National Park Service| date = 2008-03-26| url = http://www.nps.gov/glac/parknews/news08-11.htm| accessdate = 2010-04-14 }}</ref> In anticipation of the 100th anniversary of the park in 2010, major reconstruction of the [[Going-to-the-Sun Road]] is underway, and temporary road closures are expected through then. The [[Federal Highway Administration]] is managing the reconstruction project in cooperation with the National Park Service.<ref name="FHA">{{cite web| title =Going-to-the-Sun Road project| publisher =U.S. Department of Transportation|date=2010-04-14 |url =http://www.wfl.fhwa.dot.gov/projects/gtsr/| accessdate = 2010-04-14}}</ref> Some rehabilitation of major structures such as visitor centers and historic hotels, as well as improvements in wastewater treatment facilities and campgrounds, are expected to be completed by the anniversary date. Also planned are fishery studies for Lake McDonald, updates of the historical archives and restoration of trails.

The mandate of the National Park Service is to "...&nbsp;preserve and protect natural and cultural resources". The [[Organic Act]] of August 25, 1916, established the National Park Service as a federal agency.  One major section of the Act has often been summarized as the "Mission", "...&nbsp;to promote and regulate the use of the&nbsp;... national parks&nbsp;... which purpose is to conserve the scenery and the natural and historic objects and the wild life therein and to provide for the enjoyment of the same in such manner and by such means as will leave them unimpaired for the enjoyment of future generations."<ref name="mission">{{cite web| title =The National Park System, Caring for the American Legacy| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior|date=|url =http://www.nps.gov/legacy/mission.html| accessdate = 2010-04-14}}</ref> In keeping with this mandate, hunting is illegal in the park, as are [[mining]], [[forestry|logging]] and removal of natural or cultural resources. Additionally, [[oil exploration|oil]] and [[Natural gas|gas exploration]] and extraction are not permitted. These restrictions, however, caused a lot of conflict with the adjoining Blackfeet Indian Reservation considering that when they sold the land to the United States government it was with the stipulation of being able to maintain their usage rights of the area, many of which (such as hunting) had come into conflict with these regulations.<ref name="Spence"/> In 1974, a [[wilderness]] study was submitted to Congress which identified 95% of the area of the park as qualifying for wilderness designation. Unlike a few other parks, Glacier National Park has yet to be protected as wilderness, but National Park Service policy requires that identified areas listed in the report be managed as wilderness until Congress renders a full decision.<ref name="management1"/> Ninety-three percent of Glacier National Park is managed as wilderness, even though it has not been officially designated.<ref name="mammals">{{cite web|title =Mammals| publisher =National Park Service| url=http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/mammals.htm | date= 2008-03-05 | accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

==Geography and geology==
{{Main|Mountains and mountain ranges of Glacier National Park (U.S.)}}
[[File:Chief Mountain.jpg|thumb|[[Chief Mountain]] is an isolated peak on the easternmost boundary of the park.]]

The park is bordered on the north by Waterton Lakes National Park in Alberta, and the Flathead Provincial Forest and [[Akamina-Kishinena Provincial Park]] in British Columbia.<ref name="Akamina">{{cite web| title =Akamina-Kishinena Provincial Park| publisher =BC Parks|url =http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/bcparks/explore/parkpgs/akamina/| accessdate = 2010-04-19}}</ref> To the west, the north fork of the [[Flathead River]] forms the western boundary, while its middle fork is part of the southern boundary. The Blackfeet Indian Reservation provides most of the eastern boundary, and the [[Lewis and Clark National Forest|Lewis and Clark]] and the [[Flathead National Forest]]s form the southern and western boundary.<ref name="reservation">{{cite web| title = Nearby Attractions| publisher = National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/nearbyattractions.htm| date= 2010-01-11 |accessdate = 2010-04-19}}</ref> The remote [[Bob Marshall Wilderness Complex]] is located in the two forests immediately to the south.<ref name="bob">{{cite web| title =Great Bear Wilderness| publisher =Wilderness.net, The University of Montana |url =http://www.wilderness.net/index.cfm?fuse=NWPS&sec=wildView&WID=219| accessdate = 2010-04-19}}</ref>

The park contains a dozen large lakes and 700 smaller ones, but only 131 lakes have been named.<ref name="lakes">{{cite web| title =Lakes and Ponds| work =Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service|url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/lakesandponds.htm|date=2008-03-29 |accessdate = 2010-04-19}}</ref> Lake McDonald on the western side of the park is the longest ({{convert|9.4|mi|km}}), largest in area ({{convert|6823|acre|km2}}) and deepest ({{convert|464|ft|m}}) of these lakes. Numerous smaller lakes, known as [[tarn (lake)|tarn]]s, are located in [[cirque (landform)|cirque]]s formed by glacial erosion. Some of these lakes, like Avalanche Lake and [[Cracker Lake]], are colored an opaque turquoise by suspended glacial [[silt]], which also causes a number of streams to run milky white. The lakes of Glacier National Park remain cold year round, with temperatures rarely above {{convert|50|<U+00B0>F|<U+00B0>C|0}} at their surface.<ref name="lakes"/> Cold water lakes such as these support little [[plankton]] growth, ensuring that the lake waters are remarkably clear. The lack of plankton, however, lowers the rate of pollution filtration, and pollutants have a tendency to linger longer. Consequently, the lakes are considered environmental [[bellwether]]s as they can be quickly affected by even minor increases in pollutants.<ref name="pollution">{{cite web| title =WACAP&nbsp;<U+2013> Western Airborne Contaminants Assessment Project| publisher =National Park Service|url =http://www.nature.nps.gov/air/studies/air_toxics/wacap.cfm#Database| date=2010-02-25 |accessdate = 2010-04-19}}</ref>

Two hundred waterfalls are scattered throughout the park, however, during drier times of the year, many of these are reduced to a trickle. The largest falls include those in the [[Two Medicine]] region, McDonald Falls in the McDonald Valley and Swiftcurrent Falls in the [[Many Glacier]] area, which is easily observable and close to the Many Glacier Hotel. One of the tallest waterfalls is [[Bird Woman Falls]], which drops {{convert|492|ft|m}} from a hanging valley beneath the north slope of [[Mount Oberlin]].<ref name="birdwoman">{{cite web| title =Bird Woman Falls| publisher =World Waterfall Database|url =http://www.world-waterfalls.com/waterfall.php?num=493| date=2005-09-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-21}}</ref>

[[File:Two Medicine Lake.jpg|thumb|right|[[Two Medicine]] Lake with Sinopah Mountain]]

===Geology===

The rocks found in the park are primarily [[sedimentary rock]]s of the [[Belt Supergroup]]. They were deposited in shallow seas over 1.6&nbsp;billion to 800&nbsp;million years ago. During the formation of the [[Rocky Mountains]] 170&nbsp;million years ago one region of rocks now known as the [[Lewis Overthrust]] was forced eastward {{convert|50|mi|km|0}}. This [[Thrust fault|overthrust]] was several miles thick and hundreds of miles long.<ref name="geology">{{cite web| title=Lewis Overthrust Fault| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior|url =http://www.nature.nps.gov/geology/parks/glac/index.cfm| accessdate = 2010-09-03}}</ref> This resulted in older rocks being displaced over newer ones, so the overlying [[Proterozoic]] rocks are between 1.4 and 1.5&nbsp;billion years older than [[Cretaceous]] age rocks they now rest on.<ref name="geology"/><ref name="fieldnotes">{{cite web| title=Park Geology |work= Geology Fieldnotes| publisher =National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior |url= http://www.nature.nps.gov/geology/parks/glac/| date=2005-01-04 |accessdate = 2010-04-21}}</ref>

One of the most dramatic evidences of this overthrust is visible in the form of Chief Mountain, an isolated peak on the edge of the eastern boundary of the park rising {{convert|2500|ft|m|-2}} above the [[Great Plains]].<ref name="fieldnotes"/><ref name="formations">{{cite web|title=Geologic Formations |work= Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service|url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/geologicformations.htm |date=2008-03-29 |accessdate = 2010-04-21}}</ref> There are six mountains in the park over {{convert|10000|ft|m|-2}} in elevation, with [[Mount Cleveland (Montana)|Mount Cleveland]] at {{convert|10466|ft|m|0}} being the tallest.<ref name="peaks">{{cite peakbagger |rid=1421 |name=Glacier National Park Ranges |accessdate=2010-04-21}}</ref> Appropriately named [[Triple Divide Peak (Montana)|Triple Divide Peak]] sends waters towards the Pacific Ocean, [[Hudson Bay]], and [[Gulf of Mexico]] [[drainage basin|watershed]]s, and can effectively be considered to be the apex of the North American continent, although the mountain is only {{convert|8020|ft|m|0}} above sea level.<ref name="triple">{{cite peakbagger |pid=4815 |name=Triple Divide Peak, Montana |accessdate=2010-04-21}}</ref>
[[File:Stromatolites.jpg|thumb|right|Stromatolites found in the Siyeh Formation which has been dated to be more than one billion years old]]
The rocks in Glacier National Park are the best preserved Proterozoic sedimentary rocks in the world, and have proved to be some of the world's most fruitful sources for records of early life. Sedimentary rocks of similar age located in other regions have been greatly altered by mountain building and other metamorphic changes, and consequently fossils are less common and more difficult to observe.<ref name="sedimentary">{{cite web|title=Exposed Rocks within the Park |work= America's Volcanic Past: Montana | publisher =United States Geological Survey|url =http://vulcan.wr.usgs.gov/LivingWith/VolcanicPast/Places/volcanic_past_montana.html| date= 2003-06-11 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> The rocks in the park preserve such features as millimeter-scale lamination, ripple marks, mud cracks, salt-crystal casts, raindrop impressions, [[oolite]]s and other sedimentary bedding characteristics. Six fossilized species of [[Stromatolite]]s, which were early organisms consisting primarily blue-green [[algae]], have been documented and dated at about 1&nbsp;billion years.<ref name="formations"/> The discovery of the [[Appekunny Formation]], a well preserved rock stratum in the park, pushed back the established date for the origination of animal life a full billion years. This rock formation has bedding structures which are believed to be the remains of the earliest identified [[metazoan]] (animal) life on Earth.<ref name="fieldnotes"/>

===Glaciers===
{{Main|Glaciers in Glacier National Park (U.S.)}}
[[File:USGSglacierssince1850.jpg|thumb|right|Glacial retreat since end of [[Little Ice Age|LIA]] in 1850.]]
Glacier National Park is dominated by mountains which were carved into their present shapes by the huge glaciers of the [[last glacial maximum|last ice age]]; these glaciers have largely disappeared over the last 12,000 years.<ref name="ice age">{{cite web| title=History of Glaciers in Glacier National Park | publisher =Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center, United States Geological Survey |url= http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/climate_glaciers.htm| date= 2010-04-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> Evidence of widespread glacial action is found throughout the park in the form of [[U-shaped valley]]s, glacial cirques, [[ar<U+00EA>te]]s and large outflow lakes radiating like fingers from the base of the highest peaks.<ref name="features">{{cite web|title=Glaciers / Glacial Features | publisher =National Park Service |url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/glaciers.htm| date= 2009-09-22 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> Since the end of the ice ages, various warming and cooling trends have occurred. The last recent cooling trend was during the [[Little Ice Age]] which took place approximately between 1550 and 1850.<ref name="change">{{cite web| title=Was there a Little Ice Age and a Medieval Warm Period? | publisher =Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, United Nations Environment Programme |url= http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/070.htm| year= 2003 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> During the Little Ice Age, the glaciers in the park expanded and advanced, although to nowhere near as great an extent as they had during the Ice Age.<ref name="ice age"/>

During the middle of the 20th century, examination of the maps and photographs from the previous century provided clear evidence that the 150 glaciers known to have existed in the park a hundred years earlier had greatly retreated, and in many cases disappeared altogether.<ref name="retreat">{{cite web| title=Retreat of Glaciers in Glacier National Park | publisher =Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center, United States Geological Survey |url= http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/glacier_retreat.htm| date= 2010-04-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> Repeat photography of the glaciers, such as the pictures taken of [[Grinnell Glacier]] between 1938 and 2009 as shown, help to provide visual confirmation of the extent of glacier retreat.
