|}
In the 1980s, the [[U.S. Geological Survey]] began a more systematic study of the remaining glaciers, which continues to the present day. By 2010, 37 glaciers remained, but only 25 of these were considered to be "active glaciers" of at least {{convert|25|acre|km2}} in area.<ref name="Huffpo"/><ref name="retreat"/> Scientists generally agree that if the current climate conditions continue, most of the remaining glaciers in the park will be gone by 2030 or even as soon as 2020.<ref name="features"/> This [[retreat of glaciers since 1850|glacier retreat]] follows a worldwide pattern that has accelerated even more since 1980. Without a major climatic change in which cooler and moister weather returns and persists, the [[Glacier mass balance|mass balance]], which is the accumulation rate versus the ablation (melting) rate of glaciers, will continue to be negative and the glaciers will eventually disappear, leaving behind only barren rock.<ref name="monitoring">{{cite web| title=Monitoring and Assessing Glacier Changes and Their Associated Hydrologic and Ecologic Effects in Glacier National Park |work=Glacier Monitoring Research | publisher =Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center, United States Geological Survey |url= http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/glaciers.htm| date= 2010-04-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref>

After the end of the Little Ice Age in 1850, the glaciers in the park retreated moderately until the 1910s. Between 1917 and 1941, the retreat rate accelerated and was as high as {{convert|330|ft|m}} a year for some glaciers.<ref name="retreat"/> A slight cooling trend from the 1940s until 1979, helped to slow the rate of retreat and in a few examples some glaciers even advanced a few tens of meters. However, during the 1980s, the glaciers in the park began a steady period of loss of glacial ice, which continues as of 2010. In 1850, the glaciers in the region near [[Blackfoot Glacier|Blackfoot]] and [[Jackson Glacier]]s covered {{convert|5337|acre|km2|1}}, but by 1979, the same region of the park had glacier ice covering only {{convert|1828|acre|km2|1}}. Between 1850 and 1979, 73% of the glacial ice had melted away.<ref name="hall">{{cite journal| last =Hall| first =Myrna| coauthors =Daniel Fagre| title =Modeled Climate-Induced glacier change in Glacier National Park, 1850<U+2013>2100| volume =53| issue =2| publisher =Bioscience| month =February | year =2003| url =http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/glacier_model.htm|accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref> At the time the park was created, Jackson Glacier was part of Blackfoot Glacier, but the two have separated into two glaciers since.<ref name="jackson">{{cite web| title =Blackfoot-Jackson Glacier Complex 1914<U+2013>2009| publisher =Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center, United States Geological Survey| url =http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/repeatphoto/blackfoot.htm|date= 2010-04-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-24}}</ref>

The impact of glacier retreat on the park's ecosystems is not fully known, but cold water dependent plant and animal species could suffer due to a loss of habitat. Reduced seasonal melting of glacial ice may also affect stream flow during the dry summer and fall seasons, reducing water table levels and increasing the risk of forest fires. The loss of glaciers will also reduce the aesthetic visual appeal that glaciers provide to visitors.<ref name="hall"/>

===Climate===
[[File:Big Drift.jpg|thumb|The [[Big Drift]] covering the [[Going-to-the-Sun Road]] as photographed on March 23, 2006]]

As the park spans the Continental Divide, and has more than {{convert|7000|ft|m}} in elevation variance, many climates and [[microclimate]]s are found in the park. As with other alpine systems, average temperature usually drop as elevation increases.<ref name="montane">{{cite web| title =Montane Forest Ecotype|publisher =State of Montana| url =http://fwpiis.mt.gov/content/getItem.aspx?id=26470| accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The western side of the park, in the Pacific watershed, has a milder and wetter climate. Precipitation is greatest during the winter and spring averaging {{convert|2|to|3|in|mm|-1}} per month. Snowfall can occur at any time of the year, even in the summer, and especially at higher altitudes. The winter can bring prolonged cold waves, especially on the eastern side of the Continental Divide. Snowfalls are significant over the course of the winter, with the largest accumulation occurring in the west. During the tourist season daytime high temperatures average 60 to 70 <U+00B0>F (15 to 20 <U+00B0>C), and nighttime lows usually drop into the 40 <U+00B0>F (5 <U+00B0>C) range. Temperatures in the high country may be much cooler. In the lower western valleys, daytime highs in the summer may reach {{convert|90|F|C|-1}}.<ref name="weather">{{cite web| title =Weather|publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/weather.htm| date= 2006-12-21 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>
[[File:Going to sun road.jpg|thumb|[[Going-to-the-Sun Road]] in summer]]
Rapid temperature changes have been noted in the region, and in [[Browning, Montana]], which is just east of the park in the Blackfeet Reservation, a world record temperature drop of 100&nbsp;<U+00B0>F (56&nbsp;<U+00B0>C) in only 24 hours occurred on the night of January 23<U+2013>24, 1916, when thermometers plunged from {{convert|44|to|-56|F|C}}.<ref name="record">{{cite web| title =Top Ten Montana Weather Events of the 20th Century| work =National Weather Service Unveils Montana's Top Ten Weather/Water/Climate Events of the 20th Century| publisher =National Weather Service| url =http://www.wrh.noaa.gov/tfx/tx.php?wfo=tfx&type=html&loc=text&fx=topweather| accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

Glacier National Park has a highly regarded global [[climate change]] research program. Based in West Glacier, with its main headquarters in [[Bozeman, Montana]], the [[U.S. Geological Survey]] has performed scientific research on specific climate change studies since 1992. In addition to the study of the retreating glaciers, research performed includes forest modeling studies in which fire ecology and habitat alterations are analyzed. Additionally, changes in alpine vegetation patterns are documented, watershed studies in which stream flow rates and temperatures are recorded frequently at fixed gauging stations, and atmospheric research in which [[UV-B]] radiation, ozone and other atmospheric gases are analyzed over time. The research compiled contributes to a broader understanding of climate changes in the park. The data collected, when compared to other facilities scattered around the world, help to correlate these climatic changes on a global scale.<ref name="global">{{cite web| last =Fagre| first =Daniel| title =Global Change Research A Focus on Mountain Ecosystems| publisher =U.S. Geological Survey, Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center| date =2010-04-13| url =http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/global.htm| accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref><ref name="wmi">{{cite web| title =Response of Western Mountain Ecosystems to Climatic Variability and Change: The Western Mountain Initiative| publisher =U.S. Geological Survey, Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center| date =2009-02-11| url =http://biology.usgs.gov/ecosystems/global_change/western_mountain.html| accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

Glacier is considered to have excellent air and water quality. No major areas of dense human population exist anywhere near the region and industrial effects are minimized due to a scarcity of factories and other potential contributors of pollutants.<ref name="airquality">{{cite web| title =Air Quality| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/airquality.htm | date= 2008-03-29 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> However, the sterile and cold lakes found throughout the park are easily contaminated by airborne pollutants that fall whenever it rains or snows, and some evidence of these pollutants has been found in park waters. The pollution level is currently viewed as negligible, and the park lakes and waterways have a water quality rating of A-1, the highest rating given by the state of Montana.<ref name="waterquality">{{cite web| title =Water Quality| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/waterquality.htm | date= 2008-03-27 |accessdate = 2010-04-14}}</ref>

==Wildlife and ecology==
{{See also|Ecology of the Rocky Mountains}}

===Flora===
[[File:Beargrass.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Beargrass]] is a tall flowering plant commonly found throughout the park.]]

Glacier is part of a large preserved [[ecosystem]] collectively known as the "Crown of the Continent Ecosystem", all of which is primarily untouched wilderness of a pristine quality. Virtually all the plants and animals which existed at the time European explorers first entered the region are present in the park today.<ref name="bio">{{cite web| title =The Crown of the Continent Ecosystem| work= Biodiversity |publisher =National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/bio1.htm#Crown | accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

A total of over 1,132 plant species have been identified parkwide.<ref name="flora">{{cite web| title =Plants|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/plants.htm | date= 2008-03-05 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The predominantly [[coniferous]] forest is home to various species of trees such as the [[Engelmann spruce]], [[Douglas fir]], [[subalpine fir]], [[limber pine]] and [[western larch]], which is a [[deciduous]] conifer, producing cones but losing its needles each fall. [[Populus sect. Aegiros|cottonwood]] and [[aspen]] are the more common deciduous trees and are found at lower elevations, usually along lakes and streams.<ref name="montane"/> The [[tree line|timberline]] on the eastern side of the park is almost {{convert|800|ft|m|0}} lower than on the western side of the Continental Divide, due to exposure to the colder winds and weather of the Great Plains. West of the Continental Divide, the forest receives more moisture and is more protected from the winter, resulting in a more densely populated forest with taller trees. Above the forested valleys and mountain slopes, alpine [[tundra]] conditions prevail, with grasses and small plants eking out an existence in a region that enjoys as little as three months without snow cover.<ref name="wildflowers">{{cite web| title =Wildflowers|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/wildflowers.htm|date= 2008-03-25 | accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Thirty species of plants are found only in the park and surrounding National Forests.<ref name="flora"/> [[Beargrass]], a tall flowering plant, is commonly found near moisture sources, and is relatively widespread during July and August. Wildflowers such as [[Mimulus|monkeyflower]], [[lilium|glacier lily]], [[fireweed]], [[Balsamorhiza|balsamroot]] and [[Indian paintbrush]] are also common.

The forested sections fall into three major climatic zones. The west and northwest are dominated by spruce and fir and the southwest by [[Thuja plicata|redcedar]] and [[Tsuga|hemlock]]; the areas east of the Continental Divide are a combination of mixed pine, spruce, fir and prairie zones. The cedar-hemlock groves along the [[Lake McDonald]] valley are the easternmost examples of this Pacific climatic ecosystem.<ref name="forest">{{cite web| title =Forests|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/forests.htm| date= 2008-03-29 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

[[Whitebark pine]] communities have been heavily damaged due to the effects of [[Cronartium ribicola|blister rust]], a non native fungus. In Glacier and the surrounding region, 30% of the Whitebark pine trees have died and over 70% of the remaining trees are currently infected. The Whitebark pine provides a high fat pine cone seed, commonly known as the pine nut, that is a favorite food of [[red squirrel]]s and [[Clark's Nutcracker]]. Both [[grizzly bear|grizzlies]] and [[American Black Bear|black bears]] are known to raid squirrel caches of the pine nuts, and it is one of the bears' favorite foods. Between 1930 and 1970, efforts to control the spread of blister rust were unsuccessful, and continued destruction of whitebark pines appears likely, with attendant negative impacts on dependent species.<ref name="whitebark">{{cite web| title =Whitebark Pine Communities| publisher =Northern Rocky Mountain Science Center, U.S. Geological Survey| date =2010-04-13| url =http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/whitebar.htm | accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

===Fauna===
{{Main|Birds of Glacier National Park (U.S.)|Mammals of Glacier National Park (U.S.)}}
[[File:Grizzlybears ChrisServheenUSFWS.jpg|thumb|Approximately 300 Grizzly bears are believed to exist in the park as of 2008.<ref name="mammals"/>]]

Virtually all the historically known plant and animal species, with the exception of the [[bison]] and woodland [[caribou]], are present, providing [[biologists]] an intact ecosystem for plant and animal research. Two [[threatened species]] of mammals, the grizzly bear and the [[Canadian Lynx|Canadian lynx]], are found in the park.<ref name="mammals"/> Although their numbers remain at historical levels, both are listed as threatened because in virtually every other region of the U.S. outside of [[Alaska]], they are either extremely rare or absent from their historical range. On average, one or two bear attacks on humans occur each year; since the creation of the park in 1910, there have been a total of 10 bear related deaths.<ref name="bear">{{cite web| title =If you encounter a bear |work=Bears| publisher =National Park Service| url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/bears2.htm#Pepper| archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061222220732/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/bears2.htm| archivedate=2006-12-22 | accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The number of grizzlies and lynx in the park is not known for certain, but park biologists believed as of 2008 that there were just above 300 grizzlies in the park; a study commenced in 2001 hoped to determine the number of lynx.<ref name="mammals"/><ref name="lynx">{{cite web| last =Hudson| first =Laura| title =Lynx inventories under way in the Intermountain Region| publisher =National Park Service| url= http://www2.nature.nps.gov/yearinreview/yir2001/02_management/02_1_hudson.html | date= 2008-01-10 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The exact population figures for grizzlies and the smaller [[American Black Bear|black bear]] are not known but biologists are using a variety of methods to try and determine  an accurate population range.<ref name="dna">{{cite web| last =Kendall| first =Katherine| coauthors=Lisette Waits|title =Greater Glacier Bear DNA Project 1997<U+2013>2002|work=Northern Divide Grizzly Bear Project| publisher =United States Geological Survey| url=http://www.nrmsc.usgs.gov/research/glac_beardna.htm |date= 2010-04-13 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Another study has indicated that the [[wolverine]], another very rare mammal in the lower 48 states, continues to reside in the park.<ref name="wolverine">{{cite web| last =Copeland| first =Jeff| coauthors=Rick Yates, Len Ruggiero|title =Wolverine Population Assessment in Glacier National Park, Montana| publisher =Wolverine Foundation| date = 2003-06-16| url=http://wolverinefoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/gnpprog_sprng03.pdf |format=PDF|accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Other large mammals such as the [[mountain goat]] (the official park symbol), [[Bighorn Sheep|bighorn sheep]], [[moose]], [[elk]], [[Mule Deer|mule deer]], [[white-tailed deer]], [[coyote]], and the rarely seen [[Cougar|mountain lion]], are either plentiful or common.<ref name="check">{{cite web| title =Mammal Checklist|work=Mammals of Glacier National Park Field Checklist| publisher =National Park Service|url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/mammalchecklist.htm| date= 2006-12-21 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Unlike in [[Yellowstone National Park]], which commenced a [[Mackenzie Valley Wolf|wolf]] reintroduction program in the 1990s, it is believed that wolves recolonized the park naturally during the 1980s.<ref name="wolf">{{cite web|title =Gray Wolf&nbsp;<U+2013> Canis lupus |work=Montana Field Guide| publisher =State of Montana| url=http://fieldguide.mt.gov/detail_AMAJA01030.aspx |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Sixty-two species of mammals have been documented including [[badger]], [[Northern River Otter|river otter]], [[porcupine]], [[mink]], [[marten]], [[fisher (animal)|fisher]], six species of [[bat]]s and numerous other smaller mammals.<ref name="check"/>

A total 260 species of birds have been recorded, with raptors such as the [[Bald Eagle]], [[Golden Eagle]], [[Peregrine Falcon]], [[Osprey]] and several species of [[hawk]]s residing year round.<ref name="birds">{{cite web|title =Birds
|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/birds.htm |date= 2010-01-12 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The [[Harlequin Duck]] is a colorful species of waterfowl found in the lakes and waterways. The [[Great Blue Heron]], [[Bewick's Swan|Tundra Swan]], [[Canada Goose]] and [[American Wigeon]] are species of waterfowl more commonly encountered in the park. [[Great Horned Owl]], [[Clark's Nutcracker]], [[Steller's Jay]], [[Pileated Woodpecker]] and [[Cedar Waxwing]] reside in the dense forests along the mountainsides, and in the higher altitudes, the [[White-tailed Ptarmigan|Ptarmigan]], [[American sparrow|Timberline Sparrow]] and [[Mountain finch|Rosy Finch]] are the most likely to be seen.<ref name="birds"/><ref name="birds2">{{cite web|title =Birds of Glacier National park Field Checklist| publisher =National Park Service| url=http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/birds2005.pdf| archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20061229224311/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/birds2005.pdf| archivedate=2006-12-29| format=PDF  |year= 2005 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> The Clark's Nutcracker is less plentiful than in past years due to the decline in the number of [[Whitebark Pine|whitebark pines]].<ref name="whitebark"/>

Because of the colder climate, [[ectothermic]] reptiles are all but absent, with two species of [[garter snake]]s and the [[Painted Turtle|western painted turtle]] being the only three reptile species proven to exist.<ref name="reptiles">{{cite web| title =Reptiles|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/reptiles.htm| date= 2008-03-05 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> Similarly, only six species of [[amphibian]]s are documented, although those species exist in large numbers. After a forest fire in 2001, a few  park roads were temporarily closed the following year to allow thousands of [[Western toad]]s to migrate to other areas.<ref name="toad">{{cite web| title =Amphibians|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/amphibians.htm| accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

Glacier is also home to the [[endangered species|endangered]] [[bull trout]] which is illegal to possess and must be returned to the water if caught inadvertently.<ref name="bull trout">{{cite web| title =Preserving Glacier's Native Bull Trout|publisher =National Park Service|url= http://www.glaciermt.com/pdf/bulltrout.pdf| format=PDF|accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref> A total of 23 species of fish reside in park waters and native game fish species found in the lakes and streams include the [[cutthroat trout]], [[Northern Pike|northern pike]], [[Coregonus|mountain whitefish]], [[Sockeye salmon|Kokanee salmon]] and [[grayling (species)|grayling]]. Introduction in previous decades of [[Lake trout]] and other non-native fish species have greatly impacted some native fish populations, especially the bull trout and west slope cutthroat trout.<ref name="fish">{{cite web| title =Fish|work=Nature and Science| publisher =National Park Service| url= http://www.nps.gov/glac/naturescience/fish.htm| date= 2008-03-05 |accessdate = 2010-04-18}}</ref>

===Fire ecology===
[[File:GNP Wildfires 2003.jpg|thumb|Wildfires burned 10% of the park in 2003.]]

[[Wildfire|Forest fire]]s were viewed for many decades as a threat to protected areas such as forests and parks. As a better understanding of [[fire ecology]] developed after the 1960s, forest fires were understood to be a natural part of the ecosystem. The earlier policies of suppression resulted in the accumulation of dead and decaying trees and plants which would normally have been reduced had fires been allowed to burn. Many species of plants and animals actually need wildfires to help replenish the soil with nutrients and to open up areas that allow grasses and smaller plants to thrive.<ref name="fire2">{{cite web| title =A Fire Ecosystem | work =Glacier National Park Wildland Fire Management| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_2.htm| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20061229021527/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_2.htm| archivedate =2006-12-29| accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>
Glacier National Park has a fire management plan which ensures that human-caused fires are generally suppressed as they always have been. In the case of natural fires, the fire is monitored and suppression is dependent on the size and threat a fire may pose to human safety and structures.<ref name="fire3">{{cite web| title =Working With Fire: a look at Fire Management
 | work =Glacier National Park Wildland Fire Management| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_3.htm| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20061230052749/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_3.htm| archivedate =2006-12-30| accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

Increased population and the growth of suburban areas near parklands, has led to the development of what is known as Wildland Urban Interface Fire Management, in which the park cooperates with adjacent property owners in improving safety and fire awareness. This approach is common to many other protected areas. As part of this program, houses and structures near the park are designed to be more fire resistant. Dead and fallen trees are removed from near places of human habitation, reducing the available fuel load and the risk of a catastrophic fire, and advance warning systems are developed to help alert property owners and visitors about forest fire potentials during a given period of the year.<ref name="urban">{{cite web| title =Wildland Urban Interface | work =Glacier National Park Wildland Fire Management| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_4.htm| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20061212051929/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fire_4.htm| archivedate =2006-12-12 | accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref> Glacier National Park has an average of 14 fires with {{convert|5000|acre|km2}} burnt each year.<ref name="fire4">{{cite web| title =Fire in Glacier National Park | work =Glacier National Park Wildland Fire Management| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fires.htm| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20061205053836/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/resources/fires.htm| archivedate =2006-12-05 | accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref> In 2003, {{convert|136000|acre|km2}} burned in the park after a five year drought and a summer season of almost no precipitation. This was the most area transformed by fire since the creation of the park in 1910.<ref name="fire"/>

==Recreation==
[[File:Jammer.jpg|thumb|right|Glacier National Park Red Bus]]

Glacier is distant from major cities, and the closest airport is at [[Kalispell, Montana]], southwest of the park. Amtrak trains stop at East and West Glacier. A fleet of restored 1930s [[White Motor Company]] coaches, called [[Red jammer]]s, offer tours on all the main roads in the park. The drivers of the buses are called "Jammers," due to the gear-jamming that formerly occurred during the vehicles' operation. The tour buses were rebuilt in 2001. The buses were rebuilt by Ford Motor Company. The bodies were removed from their original chassis and built on modern Ford E-Series van chassis.<ref>[http://www.seriouswheels.com/cars/top-1930s-White-Glacier-National-Park-Red-Bus.htm 1930s White Glacier National Park Red Bus<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> They were also converted to run on [[propane]], to lessen their environmental impact.<ref name="reds">{{cite web| author= Vanderbilt, Amy M |year= 2002 |title=On the Road Again: Glacier National Park's Red Buses | publisher =National Park Service| url =http://crm.cr.nps.gov/archive/25-05/25-05-06.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

A number of historic wooden tour boats, some dating back to the 1920s, operate on several of the larger lakes. Several of these boats have been in continuous seasonal operation on the major lakes of Glacier National Park since 1927 and carry up to 80 tourists.<ref name="boats">{{cite web| title =Our Historic Wooden Boats | publisher =Glacier Park Boat Company| url =http://www.glacierparkboats.com/historic.htm | accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

Hiking is a popular activity in the park.  Over half of the visitors to the park report taking a hike on the park's nearly {{convert|700|mi|km|0}} of trails.<ref name="trails">{{cite web| author= Hayden, Bill |date= 2008-10-01 |title =Hiking the Trails | publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/hikingthetrails.htm | accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref> {{convert|110|mi|km|0}} of the [[Continental Divide National Scenic Trail]] spans most of the distance of the park north to south, with a few alternative routes at lower elevations if high altitude [[mountain pass|passes]] are closed due to snow. Due to the presence of bears and other large mammals, dogs are not permitted on any trails in the park, though they are permitted at front country campsites that can be accessed by a vehicle, and along paved roads. Anyone entering the United States over land or waterway from Canada must have an appropriate passport with them.<ref name="passport">{{cite web| title =Trail Status Report |publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/trailstatusreports.htm| date= 2009-06-22 |accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

[[File:GardenWall.jpg|thumb|right|A group of hikers follows the [[Garden Wall]] section of the trail, just north of the [[Logan Pass]] visitor center.  The fog is from a low-lying cloud in the valley. A red "jammer" bus can be seen on [[Going-to-the-Sun Road]] down below.]]

Numerous day hiking options are available throughout the park.  Backcountry camping is allowed at campsites along the trails.  A permit is required, which can be obtained from certain visitor centers or arranged for in advance. Much of Glacier's backcountry is usually inaccessible to hikers until early June due to accumulated snowpack and potential avalanche risk, and many trails at higher altitudes remain snow packed until July. The major campgrounds that allow vehicle access are found throughout the park, most of which are near one of the larger lakes. The campgrounds at [[St. Mary, Montana|St. Mary]] and at Apgar are open year round, but conditions are considered primitive in the off-season, as the restroom facilities are closed and there is no running water. All campgrounds with vehicle access are usually open from mid-June until mid-September.<ref name="backcountry">{{cite web| title =Backcountry Guide 2006 |publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/BCGuide-web.pdf| archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20061230223619/http://www.nps.gov/archive/glac/pdf/BCGuide-web.pdf| archivedate =2006-12-30| format=PDF|accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref> Guide and shuttle services are also available.

Fishing is a popular activity in the park and some of the finest [[fly fishing]] in North America can be found in the streams that flow through the park. Though the park requires that those fishing understand the regulations, no permit is required to fish the waters within the park boundary. The endangered bull trout must be released immediately back to the water if caught, otherwise, the regulations on limits of catch per day are liberal.<ref name="fishregs">{{cite web| title =Fishing Regulations 2008<U+2013>2009| publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/upload/08Fishing.pdf |format=PDF | accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

Winter recreation activities in Glacier are limited. [[Snowmobile|Snowmobiling]] is illegal throughout the park, but [[cross-country skiing]] is permitted in the lower altitude valleys away from potential avalanche zones.<ref name="winter">{{cite web| title =Operating Hours & Seasons |publisher =National Park Service| url =http://www.nps.gov/glac/planyourvisit/hours.htm|date=2010-01-05 |accessdate =2010-04-18}}</ref>

